														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2783835">
									

<p>I'm rather meh on this. Outside of the piece itself, writing something with elements you <em>know</em> most readers won't have installed/activated and then asking/expecting them to do so is a terrible idea.</p>
<p>For the piece&#8230; meh? The broken English thing is blown way out of proportion compared to the Alexylva SCP translations I can remember. The tone in those was archaic, this reads like you ran it back and forth trough translation software a few times. There was no pattern to it either; just, sometimes it follows normal sentence structure, sometimes it doesn't.</p>
<p>All the random mystical details and the extent to which they combined with modern stuff felt random entirely for randomness's sake, as did the vastly different styles between the images. I definitely got some minor Night Vale vibes there, but in Night Vale that's the whole point. There were a few parts that I quite enjoyed, but not enough to make up for how un-interestingly inconsistent this was.</p>
<p>(Edit: For a clear example, the titles of the people involved in the paper don't read like you were trying to re-interpret ancient positions. They read like you threw them together at random.)</p>
<p>-1</p>

							</div>

								
